nistrators and librarians; public and school library cooperation; promising practices; and state and federal roles for school library development.\n\nIn 1960, Mahar published ''State Department of Education Responsibilities for School Libraries'' (U.S. Department of Health, Education, and Welfare, Office of Education, 1960). The document reported on a study conducted by the Library Services Branch of the USOE, done at the request of the Council of Chief State School Officers. The report set forth the responsibilities and services of school libraries as interpreted by state school systems.<ref name=\"LibBio\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maher, Mary Hellen}}\n[[Category:Writers from Schenectady, New York]]\n[[Category:American librarians]]\n[[Category:Columbia University School of Library Service alumni]]\n[[Category:University at Albany, SUNY alumni]]\n[[Category:1913 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-St. John\u2019s University/WP:WCWproject (Spelling and typography)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Hellen_Maher"}
{"title_page": "International Motor Show Germany", "text_new": "{{short description|Annual German motor show}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n| name         =\n| native_name  = Internationale Automobil-Ausstellung\n| native_name_lang = ger\n| logo         = Logo_IAA.svg\n| image        = IAA Frankfurt 2007.jpg\n| caption      = The [[Messe Frankfurt|Frankfurt Trade Fair]] during the 2007 Frankfurt Motor Show with the [[Messeturm]] in the background\n| status       = Active\n| genre        = [[Auto show]]\n| begins       =\n| ends         =\n| frequency    = Annual (Passenger vehicles in odd years, commercial vehicles in even years)\n| venue        = [[Messe Frankfurt]] <small>(Passenger vehicles)</small> <br/> [[Hanover Fairground]] <small>(Commercial vehicles)</small>\n| coordinates  = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| country      = {{flag|Germany}}\n| years_active = 1897\u2013present\n| prev         = {{date|2017-09-14|}} \u2013 {{date|2017-09-24|}} <small>(Passenger vehicles)</small>\n| next         =\n| participants =\n| attendance   = See [[#Attendance|here]].\n| area         =\n| budget       =\n| activity     =\n| patron       =\n| organised    = [[Verband der Automobilindustrie]]\n| filing       = <!-- Filing status -->\n| people       =\n| member       =\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.iaa.de/en/}}\n}}\nThe '''International Motor Show Germany''' or simply '''International Motor Show''', in German known as the '''''Internationale Automobil-Ausstellung''''' (''IAA'' \u2013 International Automobile Exhibition), is the world's largest [[motor show]]. It is held annually, with passenger vehicles (including some motorcycles) being displayed in odd-numbered years in [[Frankfurt am Main]], and commercial vehicles in even-numbered years in [[Hanover]], [[Germany]]. Before 1991, the show was held solely in Frankfurt. For 2021 and beyond, the show will be held in Munich.\n\nThe IAA is organized by the ''[[Verband der Automobilindustrie]]'' (VDA&nbsp;\u2013 Association of the German Automotive Industry) and is scheduled by the [[Organisation Internationale des Constructeurs d'Automobiles]]. Formerly, the show in Frankfurt occupied twelve buildings.\n\n==History==\nIn 1897 the first IAA was held at the Hotel Bristol in [[Berlin]], with a total of eight motor vehicles on display.<ref name=1st-iaa>{{cite web|title=IAA: Frankfurt International Car Show|url=http://www.around-germany.com/1655/iaa-frankfurt-international-car-show/|publisher=Around-Germany.com|accessdate=2014-10-18|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018150648/http://www.around-germany.com/1655/iaa-frankfurt-international-car-show/|archivedate=2014-10-18}}</ref> As the automobile became more known and accepted, the IAA became a fixed event in Germany, with at least one held every year, usually in Berlin. From 1905\u20131907, there were two per year, as the production had increased to an industrial level. In the next years the show was suspended due to the ongoing [[World War I]], and was then reinstated in 1921 with 67 automobile manufacturers displaying 90 vehicles under the motto \"comfort\".\n\nDespite the still perceptible after-effects of the global recession, the 22nd IAA was held in Berlin in 1931, with a total of 295,000 visitors. For the first time the exhibition included [[front-wheel drive]] vehicles. In 1939, the 29th installation of the event gathered a total of 825,000 visitors \u2013 an all-time record at that time. The new [[Volkswagen]] was presented for the first time, which later came to be known as the [[Volkswagen Beetle|Beetle]]. This was the last IAA before it was again suspended during [[World War II]], after which Germany and Berlin was divided, with West-Berlin being isolated within Communist East Germany. From 1947\u20131949, West Germany\u2019s automobile and accessories manufacturers took part in the export trade fair in [[Hanover]]. The automobile industry\u2019s hall acted like a magnet on the public, with a great number of visitors coming to the show. In 1951 the show was held on the [[Messe Frankfurt]] for the first time. The event, which was held in April, attracted a total of 570,000 visitors, with exhibits including the first [[Large goods vehicle|HGV]] to have a [[turbo diesel]] engine. Just six months later, in September 1951, a second exhibition in Berlin was held, gathering 290,000 visitors. From then on, the German automobile industry bade farewell to its traditional exhibition site in Berlin and relocated the motor show completely to Frankfurt. The IAA was also rescheduled to only take place every other year.\n\nIn 1989 the last IAA to feature both passenger cars and commercial vehicles in one show confirmed that the exhibition site in Frankfurt was now too small for this major event. Almost 2,000 exhibitors squeezed onto an exhibition site measuring 252,000 square metres. More than 1.2 million visitors attended the event. Because of the high demand, it was no longer possible to meet exhibitors\u2019 requirements for adequate exhibition stands. In view of this, the [[Verband der Automobilindustrie|VDA]] decided to split the IAA from now on, with a focus on passenger vehicles in odd years, and a focus on commercial vehicles in even years. The first IAA focused solely on \"passenger cars\", held in 1991, was a huge success. A total of 1,271 exhibitors from 43 countries displayed their new products and innovations. With more than 935,000 visitors, the IAA Passenger Cars was extremely well attended. In 1992 the first IAA \"commercial vehicles\" took place in [[Hanover]], [[Germany]]. It saw 1,284 exhibitors from 29 countries and gathered 287,000 people, 66 per cent being trade visitors.\n\nIn 2001 the [[September 11 attacks]] on the World Trade Center in New York cast a shadow over the IAA in Frankfurt. The exhibition went ahead all the same. As a mark of solidarity with the victims and their dependants, all show elements and loud music as well as the official opening ceremony with the Federal Chancellor were cancelled. VDA President Gottschalk explained this decision: \"Because we could not permit terrorist forces to take away our freedom of action. And because, as a key international sector, we have a responsibility not to allow things to grind to a halt.\" In an impressive manner, the general public confirmed that this indeed was the right decision to take: More than 800,000 people visited this \"quiet IAA\".\n\nDuring the [[Great Recession]], in 2009, the IAA Cars proved to be a magnet for visitors. Around 850,000 people visited the IAA, which greatly exceeded the target of 750,000. This IAA, which took place under the headline \"A Moving Experience\", showed where the mobility of tomorrow is heading. A huge number of options were presented at the IAA, ranging from the mild hybrid and the plug-in hybrid to the all-electric car, fuel cells and hydrogen power.\n\nIn 2011 the 63rd IAA featured the all-new \"Hall of Electric Mobility\", a first-timer to all Motor Shows worldwide. Additional IAA-premieres included the Electric Mobility Conference as well as the CarIT Conference dealing with the issue of connected driving.\n\n==Change of Venue Location==\n\n2019 marked the final year that IAA hosted its automotive exhibition in Frankfurt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/nearly-70-years-frankfurt-no-longer-host-iaa-111205931.html |title=After nearly 70 years, Frankfurt will no longer host the IAA motor show |work=Yahoo News |date=30 January 2020}}</ref> In the last several years, more and more manufacturers opted out of IAA or greatly downsized their presences. The marquees that specialise in high performance and luxury vehicles \u2014 such as Aston Martin, Bentley, Bugatti, Ferrari, and Rolls-Royce \u2014 were often the biggest draw at the IAA show, and they were absent from the several previous exhibitions. BMW had downsized its presence from 11,000 to 3,000 square metres.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gtspirit.com/2019/09/16/iaa-2019-downfall-frankfurt-motor-show/ |title=IAA 2019: The Downfall of the Frankfurt Motor Show |date=16 September 2019 |last=Sellmeyer |first=Des |work=GT Spirit}}</ref> The rapid decreasing number of visitors in the last several exhibitions reflected the appalling state of IAA along with the failure of Messe Frankfurt to contain the aggressive environmental protestors blocking the entrances.  \n\nThus, the contract between Messe Frankfurt and [[Verband_der_Automobilindustrie|VDA]], the IAA organiser, expired in 2019: VDA chose not to renew the contract with Messe Frankfurt, citing the aforementioned reasons. Instead, VDA indicated its intention of moving its biennual automotive exhibitions to other city for 2021 onward. The final three candidate cities were [[Berlin]], [[Hamburg]], and [[Munich]]. Four cities had submitted the bids but didn't make the final round: [[Cologne]], [[Frankfurt]], [[Hannover]], and [[Stuttgart]].\n\nOn 3 March 2020 VDA chose [[Munich]].<ref>{{cite web |title=M\u00fcnchen wird die Stadt der neuen IAA 2021 |url=https://www.iaa.de/de/pkw/newsroom/presse/pressemitteilungen/muenchen-wird-die-stadt-der-neuen-iaa-2021 |website=iaa.de |publisher=iaa |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> Munich beat out Berlin and Hamburg based on three criterias. Munich Airport is second Lufthansa hub and has many direct international flights (second to Frankfurt); Munich is home to BMW and several other high-tech industries such as Apple, Google, and many start-up companies; the city has 130,000 employees working in automobile industry. The [[Alliance_90/The_Greens|Greens]]-led city council and Bavarian state government have given the support along with 2/3 of people responding to the survey. The event will take place shortly before the start of [[Oktoberfest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tz.de/muenchen/muenchen-iaa-internationale-automobil-messe-oktoberfest-flughafen-zr-13571427.html |title=Mega-Coup f\u00fcr M\u00fcnchen fix! Die IAA kommt - am Dienstag gibt es Proteste dagegen |date=4 March 2020 |lang=de |work=TZ M\u00fcnchen}}</ref>\n\n==Major vehicle introductions==\n\n=== 1951 ===\nThe following introductions were made at the 1951 show: {{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[BMW 501]]\n*[[Automobiles Marathon]] prototype\n*[[Mercedes-Benz W187]]\n*[[Mercedes-Benz M186 engine]]\n{{col-break}}{{col-end}}\n\n=== 1955 ===\nThe following introductions were made at the 1955 show:{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[BMW 503]]\n*[[BMW 501#BMW 505 prototype|BMW 505 Prototype]]{{col-break}}{{col-end}}\n\n=== 1957 ===\nThe following introductions were made at the 1957 show:{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[DKW Junior|DKW 600]] (later called DKW Junior)\n*[[Glas Isar|Goggomobil T600]]\n*[[NSU Prinz#NSU Prinz I, II & III|NSU Prinz I]]\n{{col-break}}{{col-end}}\n\n=== 1959 ===\nThe following introductions were made at the 1959 show:{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[BMW 700]]\n*[[Borgward P100]]\n*[[Mercedes-Benz W111]] Sedan\n{{col-break}}{{col-end}}\n\n=== 1961 ===\nThe following introductions were made at the 1961 show:{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[BMW New Class|BMW 1500 Sedan]]\n*[[BMW 3200 CS]]\n*[[Glas 1004]]\n{{col-break}}{{col-end}}\n\n=== 1963 ===\nThe following introductions were made at the 1963 show:{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Alfa Romeo 105/115 Series Coup\u00e9s#Giulia Sprint GT (1963\u20131965)|Alfa Romeo Giulia Sprint GT]]\n*[[Glas 1700]]\n*[[Glas GT]]\n*[[Porsche 901]]\n{{col-break}}{{col-end}}\n\n=== 1965 ===\nThe following introductions were made at the 1965 show:{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Alfa Romeo 2600]] De Luxe\n*[[Glas 1700]] TS\n*[[Glas V8]]\n*[[Mercedes-Benz W108]]\n*[[NSU Typ 110]]\n*[[Opel Kadett B]]\n{{col-break}}{{col-end}}\n\n=== 1969 ===\nThe following introductions were made at the 1969 show:{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Audi 100 Coup\u00e9 S]]\n*[[Bitter Cars#CD|Opel Coupe Diplomat]] concept\n*[[Porsche 914]]\n{{col-break}}{{col-end}}\n\n=== 1973 ===\nThe following introductions were made at the 1973 show:\n\n* [[BMW 02 Series#2002|BMW 2002 Turbo]]\n*[[Bitter Cars#CD|Bitter CD]]\n\n=== 1977 ===\nThe following introductions were made at the 1977 show:{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Ferrari 308 GTS]]\n*[[Ford Granada (Europe)#Mark II (1977\u20131985)|Ford Granada Mark II]]\n*[[Opel Rekord Series E|Opel Rekord E]]\n{{col-break}}{{col-end}}\n\n===1979 ===\nThe 1979 Show occurred in a tough year for the automobile industry, with a focus on decreased speed limits and conserving energy, with most of Western Europe on the brink of a [[Early 1980s recession|severe recession]]. It also occurred at a time when car design was changing substantially, with hatchbacks and front-wheel drive becoming increasingly popularity, as well as demand increasing for smaller \"supermini\" cars.<ref name=\"Keesings79\">{{cite journal | title = Salon van Frankfurt is aanklacht tegen politieke machthebbers |trans-title=Frankfurt Show is an indictment of political leaders | language = nl-be | journal = Keesings Auto Magazine | location = Antwerp, Belgium | date=1979-09-15 | volume = 2 | number = 17 | pages = 16\u201318 | editor-last = Rombauts | editor-first = Walter }}</ref>\n\nThe following introductions were scheduled for the 1979 show:<ref name=Keesings79/>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Alfa Romeo 6]]\n*[[Audi 100#C2|Audi 200]]\n*[[BMW 7 Series (E23)|BMW 745i]]\n*[[Citro\u00ebn GSA]] (a facelifted version of the 1970 [[Citroen GS]], which featured a hatchback instead of its predecessor's saloon body style)\n*[[Fiat Ritmo|Fiat Ritmo Cabriolet]]\n*[[Ford Taunus TC]]3 (a facelifted version of the 1976 Taunus/[[Ford Cortina|Cortina]], which was Britain's best selling car)\n*[[Lancia Delta]] (winner of the [[European Car of the Year]] award for 1980)\n*[[Mercedes-Benz W126]] (S-class)\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Mitsubishi Lancer#1979|Mitsubishi Lancer EX]] (European premier)\n*[[Renault 5]] five-door model (joining the three-door hatchback model which had been launched in 1972)\n*[[Simca 1307|Talbot 1510]]\n*[[Volkswagen Jetta]] (saloon version of the [[Volkswagen Golf]])\n*[[Volvo 300 Series|Volvo 345]] (five-door hatchback version of the Volvo 343, launched in 1976)\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== 1981 ===\nThe following introductions were made at the 1981 show:{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n*Audi Auto 2000 concept\n*[[Bitter Cars#SC|Bitter SC convertible]]\n*Ford Probe III concept\n*Mercedes-Benz Auto 2000 concept\n*[[Opel Ascona#Ascona C (1981\u20131988)|Opel Ascona C]]\n*[[Opel Tech 1]] concept\n*[[Porsche 944]]\n*[[Volkswagen Auto 2000]] concept\n{{col-break}}{{col-end}}\n\n===1983===\n\n1983 was, in most of Western Europe, a year of recovery in the new car market, as the economy recovered from the recent recession. Many important new cars were launched at Frankfurt and elsewhere during 1983. Those launched elsewhere include the [[Austin Maestro]], [[Fiat Uno]], [[Nissan Micra]], [[Peugeot 205]] and [[Renault 11]]. The [[Opel Corsa]] (launched in [[Spain]] in September 1982) was also imported to the UK from April 1983, where it was sold as the [[Vauxhall Nova]].\n\nThe following introductions were made at the 1983 show:\n\n*[[Alfa Romeo 33]] 1.5 4x4\n*[[BMW 6 Series|BMW M635 CSi]] (high performance version of the 635 CSi, launched in 1976)\n*[[Fiat Regata]]\n*[[Ford Sierra|Ford Sierra XR4i]] (fuel-injected, high performance version of the Sierra hatchback, launched in 1982)\n*[[Mercedes-Benz 190E]] (new entry-level saloon in the [[Mercedes-Benz]] range)\n*[[Opel Junior]] concept\n*[[Renault Fuego|Renault Fuego Turbo]] (turbocharged version of the Fuego coupe, launched in 1980)\n*[[Volkswagen Golf|Volkswagen Golf MK2]]\n*Zender Vision 1S concept ([[Audi Quattro]] based) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.carstyling.ru/ru/car/1983_zender_vision_1s/|title=1983 Zender Vision 1S \u2013 \u0421\u0442\u0443\u0434\u0438\u0438|last=Site-Mechanics|website=www.carstyling.ru|access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref>\n\n===1985===\n\nThe following introductions were made at the 1985 show:\n\n*[[BMW M3]] (high performance version of the 3 Series two-door sports saloon)\n*[[Ferrari 328]]\n*[[Ferrari Mondial]] 3.2\n*[[Mercedes-Benz E Class]] estate\n*Zender Vision 2 concept\n*Porsche 959\n\n===1987===\n\nThe following introductions were made at the 1987 show:\n\n*[[Alfa Romeo 164]] (flagship [[Alfa Romeo]] saloon, and the last of four cars to be developed on the [[Type Four platform|Type Four]] platform with [[Fiat]], [[Lancia]] and [[Saab Automobile|Saab]])\n*[[Ferrari F40]] (fastest production car in the world, with a top speed of 201&nbsp;mph)\n*[[Ford Aerostar#HFX Aerostar Ghia (1987)|Ford HFX Aerostar Ghia]] concept\n*[[Lamborghini Portofino]] concept\n\n===1989===\n\nThe following introductions were made at the 1989 show:\n\n*[[Alfa Romeo SZ]] (high performance sporting coupe)\n*[[BMW 8 Series (E31)]] (luxury sporting coupe to replace the long-running 6 Series)\n*[[Fiat Uno]] (facelifted version of hugely successful supermini, in production since 1983)\n*[[Land Rover Discovery]] (mid-range 4X4 in the [[Land Rover]] section of the [[Rover Group]])\n*[[Peugeot 605]] (flagship saloon model in the [[Peugeot]] range)\n*[[Rolls-Royce Corniche#Corniche III|Rolls-Royce Corniche III]]\n*[[Rolls-Royce Silver Spirit#Mark II|Rolls-Royce Silver Spirit Mark II]]\n*[[Rolls-Royce Silver Spirit#Mark II|Rolls-Royce Silver Spur Mark II]]\n*[[SEAT Proto#SEAT Proto T (1989)|SEAT Proto T]]\n*[[Toyota 4500GT]]\n*[[Opel Calibra|Vauxhall/Opel Calibra]] (new front-wheel drive coupe from [[Vauxhall Motors|Vauxhall]]/[[Opel]])\n*Zender Fact 4 Biturbo concept\n\n===1991===\n\nThe following introductions were made at the 1991 show:\n\n*[[Audi Quattro#Audi quattro Spyder concept (1991)|Audi Quattro Spyder concept]]\n*Zender Fact 4 Spider concept\n\n===1993===\n\nThe following introductions were made at the 1993 show:\n\n* [[Audi Space Frame]] (ASF) concept\n*[[Isdera Commendatore 112i]]\n\n===1995===\nThe 1995 show ran from September 14 to September 24.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\nThe following introductions were made at the 1995 show:\n*[[BMW 5 Series]] ([[BMW 5 Series (E39)|E39]])\n*[[Citro\u00ebn Xantia]] Break (estate version of hatchback launched nearly three years earlier)\n*[[Lada 2110]] (German introduction)\n*[[Mercedes-Benz E-Class]] ([[Mercedes-Benz W210|W210]] version)\n*[[Mitsubishi Carisma]] (first European built Mitsubishi, produced at a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[Volvo]] factory)\n*[[Opel Corsa]] Eco 3\n*[[Opel Vectra]] (first version to use the Vectra nameplate for Vauxhall-branded models in the UK, replacing the [[Vauxhall Cavalier|Cavalier]] name)\n*[[Peugeot 406]]\n*[[Renault M\u00e9gane]]\n*[[SEAT C\u00f3rdoba]] SX\n*[[Toyota Granvia]]\n*[[Volvo S40]]{{col-break}}\nThe following [[concept cars]] were presented at the 1995 show:\n*[[Audi TT]] Concept (entered production in 1998)\n*[[Peugeot 406]] Evidence\n*[[Peugeot 406]] Stadium\n*[[Toyota Prius]] Prototype (entered production in 1997, imported to Europe from 2000)\n*Zender Progetto Cinque\n{{col-end}}\n\n===1997===\nThe 1997 show ran from September 11 to September 21.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\nThe following introductions were made at the 1997 show:\n*[[Alfa Romeo 156]] (winner of the [[European Car of the Year]] award for 1998)\n*[[Land Rover Freelander]] (new entry-level model in the [[Land Rover]] section of the [[Rover Group]])\n*[[Mazda 626]] Station Wagon\n*[[Mercedes-Benz A-Class#W168|Mercedes-Benz A-Class (W168)]]\n*[[Opel Astra]] (entered production in early 1998)\n*[[Porsche 911 Carrera]] (996)\n*[[Rover 200]] BRM\n*[[Volkswagen Golf]] MK4\n*[[Volvo V70]] XC\n{{col-break}}\nThe following [[concept cars]] were presented at the 1997 show:\n*[[Mini (marque)|MINI Cooper]] Prototype (entered production in 2001 under [[BMW]] ownership)\n*[[Opel Zafira]] Concept<ref name=\"AR02\">{{cite book | title = Automobil Revue 2002 | editor-last = N\u00f6tzli | editor-first = Max | publisher = B\u00fcchler Grafino AG | location = Berne, Switzerland | language = German, French | page = 454 | volume = 97 |date=2002-03-07 | isbn = 3-905-386-02-X }}</ref> (entered production just over a year later)\n*[[Peugeot 806]] Runabout Concept\n*Zender Escape 6{{col-end}}\n\n===1999===\nThe 1999 show opened on September 16, and had nearly 1,200 exhibitors from 44 countries.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\nThe following introductions were made at the 1999 show:\n*[[Audi A2]]\n*[[BMW 3 Series|BMW 328]] Touring (estate)\n*[[BMW M3]]\n*[[BMW X5 (E53)]] (first SUV in [[BMW]] range)\n*[[BMW Z8]]\n*[[Citro\u00ebn Saxo]] (facelift)\n*[[Fiat Punto]] MK2\n*[[Ford Fiesta]] (facelift of 1995 model, itself a comprehensive facelift of the model first launched in 1989)\n*[[Honda Insight]] (Honda's first petrol-hybrid model)\n*[[Hyundai Accent]] MK2\n*[[Nissan Almera]] MK2 (first British-built version of the Almera)\n*[[Opel Speedster]]/[[Vauxhall VX220]] (first two-seater sports car from Vauxhall/Opel, based on [[Lotus Elise]] chassis)\n*[[Peugeot 607]] (new flagship saloon in Peugeot range)\n*[[Renault Avantime]] (luxury sporting coupe/MPV crossover; entered full production in 2001)\n*[[Saab 9-3]] Aero\n*[[Saab 9-5]] Aero\n*[[SEAT Le\u00f3n]]\n*[[\u0160koda Fabia]]\n*[[Volkswagen Polo]] (facelift)\n{{col-break}}\n[[File:VW Concept D (IAA 1999) 1.jpg|thumb|right|[[Volkswagen Concept D]] at the 1999 Frankfurt Motor Show]]\nThe following [[concept cars]] were presented at the 1999 show:\n*[[Citro\u00ebn C6 Lignage]] (luxury saloon which was finally launched in 2005 as the [[Citroen C6]])\n*[[Opel Omega#Omega V8.com|Opel Omega V8.com]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carenthusiast.com/news2808/vauxhall.htm|title=OMEGA V8.COM \u2013 THE MULTI-MEDIA CAR OF THE FUTURE?|publisher=carenthusiast.com|accessdate=2015-05-22|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304030206/http://www.carenthusiast.com/news2808/vauxhall.htm|archivedate=2016-03-04}}</ref> (never reached full production)\n*[[Volkswagen Concept D]] (launched in 2002 as the [[Volkswagen Phaeton]])\n*Zender Thirty 7\n{{col-end}}\n\n===2001===\nThe 2001 show opened to international media on September 11, with a series of concept and production vehicle debuts kicking off in the early morning.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\nThe following introductions were made at the 2001 show:\n*[[Alfa Romeo 156]] GTA/Sportwagon GTA\n*[[Audi A4]] Avant (estate)\n*[[Audi A4]] Convertible\n*[[BMW 3 Series]] (facelift)\n*[[BMW 7 Series]]\n*[[Cadillac CTS]]\n*[[Citro\u00ebn C3]]\n*[[Ford Fiesta]]\n*[[Honda Jazz]]\n*[[Lamborghini Murcielago]]\n*[[Mercedes-Benz SL-Class]] ([[Mercedes-Benz SL-Class (R230)|R230]])\n*[[Opel Combo]]\n*[[Peugeot 206]] SW<ref name=\"autoweb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autoweb.com.au/cms/A_54429/title_Peugeots-Look-Into-the-Future-206-SW-and-307-SW-Concept-Cars-Frankfurt-Motor-Show/newsarticle.html|title=Peugeot's Look Into the Future \u2013 206 SW and 307 SW Concept Cars (Frankfurt Motor Show) \u2013 AutoWeb News<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=autoweb.com.au|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203191137/http://www.autoweb.com.au/cms/A_54429/title_Peugeots-Look-Into-the-Future-206-SW-and-307-SW-Concept-Cars-Frankfurt-Motor-Show/newsarticle.html|archivedate=2014-02-03}}</ref>\n*[[Peugeot 307]] SW<ref name=\"autoweb\"/>\n*[[Renault Avantime]]\n*[[Saab 9-5]] (facelift)\n*[[\u0160koda Superb]]\n*[[Spyker C8]] Laviolette\n*[[Toyota Corolla]]\n*[[Volkswagen Polo]]\n*[[Volvo S60]]\n{{col-break}}\n[[File:IAA 2001 018 - Flickr - Axel Schwenke.jpg|thumb|right|[[Audi A4]] Convertible at the 2001 Frankfurt Motor Show]]\nThe following [[concept cars]] were presented at the 2001 show:\n*[[Audi Avantissimo]]\n*[[Citro\u00ebn C-Crosser]]\n*[[Ford Fusion (Europe)|Ford Fusion]] Concept\n*[[Jaguar Cars|Jaguar]] R-Coup\u00e9\n*[[Hyundai Clix]]\n*[[Nissan Micra#K12|Nissan mm.e]]<ref name=\"prnewswire\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/carlos-ghosn-outlines-bold-plan-for-nissan-in-europe-71999672.html |title=Carlos Ghosn Outlines Bold Plan for Nissan in Europe |publisher=Nissan Motor Company |date=2001-09-11 |via=PR Newswire |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201205148/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/carlos-ghosn-outlines-bold-plan-for-nissan-in-europe-71999672.html |archivedate=2014-02-01 |access-date=2014-01-31 }}</ref>\n*Nissan Crossbow<ref name=\"prnewswire\"/>\n*[[Opel Frogster]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europe.autonews.com/article/20010924/ANE/109240816/frogster-puts-the-fun-back-into-opel|title=Frogster puts the fun back into Opel|publisher=europe.autonews.com|date=2001-09-24|accessdate=2015-06-13}}</ref>\n*[[Opel Signum#2001 Signum2 Concept|Opel Signum2]] concept\n*[[Renault Talisman]]\n*[[Saab 9-X]]\n*[[SEAT Arosa]] Racer\n*SEAT Arosa City Cruiser\n*[[SEAT Tango]]\n*[[Suzuki]] GSX-R/4\n*Volvo PCC 2\n*Zender Straight 8\n{{col-end}}\n\n* Originally, the [[Opel Vectra]] C was due to d\u00e9but with the [[Saab 9-3]], but in July 2001, it was announced that delays had forced [[General Motors]] to postpone the introduction. Both cars were eventually introduced in March 2002, at the [[Geneva Motor Show]].<ref name=\"Autotrader.com\">[http://www.autotrader.com/research/article/4099/spy-shots-2003-saab-9-3.jsp/Autotrader.com/] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518081843/http://www.autotrader.com/research/article/4099/spy-shots-2003-saab-9-3.jsp/Autotrader.com/|date=2015-05-18}}</ref>\n\n===2003===\nFor the first time, the passenger car-only exhibition in Frankfurt broke the barrier of one million visitors. It featured 2,000 exhibitors from 42 countries.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\nThe following introductions were made at the 2003 show:\n*[[Alfa Romeo 166]] (facelift)\n*[[Alpina B7 (E65)]] (production version)\n*[[Alpina Roadster S]]\n*[[Aston Martin DB9]]\n*[[Citro\u00ebn C2]]\n*[[BMW 5 Series]]\n*[[BMW 6 Series (E63)|BMW 6 Series]]\n*[[BMW X3]]\n*[[Daewoo Lacetti]]\n*[[Jaguar X-Type]] Estate\n*[[Kia Picanto]]\n*[[Land Rover Freelander]] (facelift)\n*[[Lexus LS430]]\n*[[Maserati Quattroporte]]\n*[[Mazda 3]]\n*[[Mercedes-Benz SLR McLaren]]\n*[[Mitsubishi Outlander]]\n*[[Opel Astra]]\n*[[Opel Vectra]] Caravan (estate)\n*[[Porsche Carrera GT]]\n*[[SEAT Altea]]\n*[[Volkswagen Golf]] MK5\n*[[Volvo S40]]\n{{col-break}}\n[[File:Porsche 996 GT3 RS.jpg|thumb|right|[[Porsche 996 GT3]] RS at the 2003 Frankfurt Motor Show]]\nThe following major [[concept cars]] were presented at the 2003 show:\n*Citro\u00ebn C-Airlounge\n*[[Ford Visos]]\n*[[Ford Focus Station Wagon Restyling]] (2003)\n*[[Lancia Fulvia]] Coup\u00e9 Concept\n*Mazda Kusabi\n*[[Mitsubishi i]]\n*Nissan Dunehawk\n*[[Opel Insignia]] Concept\n*[[Peugeot 407|Peugeot 407 Elixir]]\n*[[Renault Be Bop]]\n*[[Saab 9-3]] Sport Hatch\n*SEAT Altea Prototipo\n*[[\u0160koda Roomster]]\n*Suzuki Concept S2\n*[[Toyota CS&S]]\n*[[Volkswagen Concept R]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n===2005===<!-- This section is linked from [[Porsche Cayenne]] -->\nThe exhibition focused strongly on future solutions such as [[hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid]], [[Hydrogen vehicle|hydrogen]], [[flex-fuel]] and [[Selective catalytic reduction|SCR]] technologies for reducing [[NOx]] emissions. There were around 940,000 visitors to the 2005 show.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\nThe following introductions were made at the 2005 show:\n* [[Audi Q7]]<ref name=\"FMS 2005 Page 1\">{{cite web|title=CDN Frankfurt Motor Show 2005 \u2013 Page 1|url=http://archive.cardesignnews.com/autoshows/2005/frankfurt/highlights/index.php|publisher=CarDesignNews.com|accessdate=2013-04-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131128081249/http://archive.cardesignnews.com/autoshows/2005/frankfurt/highlights/index.php|archivedate=2013-11-28}}</ref>\n* [[Audi S6]]\n* [[Bentley Azure (2006)|Bentley Azure]]\n* [[Bufori Motor Car Company|Bufori MKIII La Joya]]\n* [[Chevrolet Aveo (T200)|Chevrolet Aveo sedan]]\n* [[Daimler Company#Revival|Daimler Super Eight]]\n* [[Fiat Grande Punto]]<ref name=\"FMS 2005 Page 3\">{{cite web|title=CDN Frankfurt Motor Show 2005 \u2013 Page 3|url=http://archive.cardesignnews.com/autoshows/2005/frankfurt/highlights/index3.php|publisher=CarDesignNews.com|accessdate=2013-04-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228152725/http://archive.cardesignnews.com/autoshows/2005/frankfurt/highlights/index3.php|archivedate=2014-12-28}}</ref>\n* [[Ford Galaxy]]<ref name=\"FMS 2005 Page 2\">{{cite web|title=CDN Frankfurt Motor Show 2005 \u2013 Page 2|url=http://archive.cardesignnews.com/autoshows/2005/frankfurt/highlights/index2.php|work=Auto news and reviews|publisher=CarDesignNews.com|accessdate=2013-04-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228153135/http://archive.cardesignnews.com/autoshows/2005/frankfurt/highlights/index2.php|archivedate=2014-12-28}}</ref>\n* [[Hyundai Getz]] (facelift)<ref>{{cite web|title=Frankfurt Motor Show 2005 \u2013 Hyundai|url=http://www.whatcar.com/car-news/frankfurt-motor-show-2005/hyundai/217026|publisher=What Car?|accessdate=2013-04-14 |date=2005-09-11}}</ref>\n* [[Honda Civic]]<ref name=\"FMS 2005 Page 3\"/>\n* [[Jaguar XK8#2006|Jaguar XK]]<ref name=\"FMS 2005 Page 2\"/>\n* [[Lamborghini Gallardo Spyder]]<ref name=\"FMS 2005 Page 4\"/>\n* [[Mercedes-Benz S-Class#W221|Mercedes-Benz S-Class]] ([[Mercedes-Benz W221|W221]])<ref name=\"FMS 2005 Page 1\"/>\n* [[Nissan Micra#C+C|Nissan Micra C+C]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nissan-global.com/EN/NEWS/2005/_STORY/050818-01-e.html|title=NISSAN AT THE 2005 IAA FRANKFURT MOTOR SHOW|website=nissan-global.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202175449/http://www.nissan-global.com/EN/NEWS/2005/_STORY/050818-01-e.html|archivedate=2014-02-02}}</ref>\n* [[Opel Vectra|Opel Vectra C (facelift)]]\n* [[Opel Signum|Opel Signum (facelift)]]\n* [[Opel Astra|Opel Astra TwinTop]]\n* [[Peugeot 407|Peugeot 407 Coup\u00e